People detection in video with YoloV3¶

Before running this playbook, make sure you have a similar tree structure in your project:

|-- yolo_people_detection.ipynb
|-- yolo-coco
    |-- coco.names
    |-- yolov3.cfg
    |-- yolov3.weights
|-- videos
    |-- library.mp4
|-- output

To run this playbook, you need files :

  • coco.names
  • yolov3.cfg
  • yolov3.weights

You can find these 3 Yolo-Coco files on the Darknet website : https://pjreddie.com/darknet/yolo/.

To find video for testing, you can download some in Pexels.com like this one https://www.pexels.com/fr-fr/video/bois-ville-homme-couple-8567035/

INPUT_VIDEO = "videos/library.mp4"
OUTPUT_VIDEO = "output/library.avi"
YOLO_RESOURCES = "yolo-coco"
CONFIDENCE = 0.5
THRESHOLD = 0.3 # Non-maxima suppression threshold 
FONT_SCALE = 1/1500 # Ratio for the font size used to describe label in the output video

Load the Coco dataset¶

The Coco dataset is a Yolo dectector pre-trained wich can identify more than 80 objects.
https://pjreddie.com/darknet/yolo/

In [3]:
# Load the Coco class labels
labelsPath = os.path.sep.join([YOLO_RESOURCES, "coco.names"])
LABELS = open(labelsPath).read().strip().split("\n")
In [4]:
# Associate one color for each label - determine the color of each rectangle in the output video
np.random.seed(55)
COLORS = np.random.randint(0, 255, size=(len(LABELS), 3), dtype="uint8")

Configuration of Yolo model¶

In this case, we use pre-trained model that can detect up to 80 objects including people, which is of interest in our case.

In [5]:
# Config file for Yolo
weightsPath = os.path.sep.join([YOLO_RESOURCES, "yolov3.weights"])
configPath = os.path.sep.join([YOLO_RESOURCES, "yolov3.cfg"])
In [6]:
# Load the pre-trained dataset to the model
net = cv2.dnn.readNetFromDarknet(configPath, weightsPath)
ln = net.getLayerNames()
ln = [ln[i[0] - 1] for i in net.getUnconnectedOutLayers()]

Detect people on an input video¶

  1. We feed our model Yolo a video that it will analyze frame by frame.
  2. We will try to detect one of the 80 objects of the Coco dataset in each frame to get probabilities.
  3. At the end of this analysis, a new video will be produced with the detected objects highlighted.
In [7]:
# Initialize the input video stream, writer for the output video, and frame dimensions

writer = None
(W, H) = (None, None)

    prop = cv2.cv.CV_CAP_PROP_FRAME_COUNT if imutils.is_cv2() else cv2.CAP_PROP_FRAME_COUNT
    total = int(vs.get(prop))
    print("[INFO] {} total frames in video".format(total))

except:
    print("[INFO] could not determine # of frames in video")
    print("[INFO] no approx. completion time can be provided")
    total = -1

In [9]:
# Loop over each frames from the video
image_index = 0
while True:
    # Read the next frame from the file
    (grabbed, frame) = vs.read()
    
    # If no frame is detected, then the video is over
    if not grabbed:
        break
    image_index += 1
        
    # Show 1 original frame in the middle of the input video
    if (image_index == int(total/2)):
        fig_width, fig_height = plt.gcf().get_size_inches()
        plt.figure(figsize=(fig_width*3,fig_height*3))
        plt.title('Original frame', fontsize=16)
        plt.axis('off')
        plt.imshow(frame)
        plt.show()
    
    # Initialize frame dimension for the first iteration
    if W is None or H is None:
        (H, W) = frame.shape[:2]
    
    # Pre-process input frame with blob
    # Input this blob to Yolo object detector and runs a forward pass to get bounding boxes with label id and associated probabilities
    blob = cv2.dnn.blobFromImage(frame, 1 / 255.0, (416, 416), swapRB=True, crop=False)
    net.setInput(blob)
    start = time.time()
    layerOutputs = net.forward(ln)
    end = time.time()
    
    # Initialize our lists of detected bounding boxes, confidences, and class IDs
    boxes = []
    confidences = []
    classIDs = []
    
    # Loop over each of the layer outputs
    for output in layerOutputs:
        # Loop over each of the detections
        for detection in output:
            # Extract the id of the class with the best confidence
            scores = detection[5:]
            classID = np.argmax(scores)
            confidence = scores[classID]
            # Check prediction is related to class "person" and confidence is good enough
            if confidence > CONFIDENCE and LABELS[classID] == "person":
                # Scale the bounding box coordinates back relative to the size of the image
                # Keeping in mind that Yolo returns the center (x, y)-coordinates of
                # the bounding box followed by the boxes width and height
                box = detection[0:4] * np.array([W, H, W, H])
                (centerX, centerY, width, height) = box.astype("int")
                # Calcule the top left corner of the box
                x = int(centerX - (width / 2))
                y = int(centerY - (height / 2))
                # Add the box to the list of bounding box with size and coordinates
                boxes.append([x, y, int(width), int(height)])
                # Add confidence related to this prediction to the list of confidence
                confidences.append(float(confidence))
                # Add class related to this prediction to the list of classIDs
                classIDs.append(classID)
                
    # Apply non-maxima suppression to suppress weak, overlapping bounding boxes
    idxs = cv2.dnn.NMSBoxes(boxes, confidences, CONFIDENCE, THRESHOLD)
    # Ensure at least one detection exists in this frame
    if len(idxs) > 0:
        # Loop over the bounding box kept after cleaning
        for i in idxs.flatten():
            # Extract the bounding box coordinates
            (x, y) = (boxes[i][0], boxes[i][1])
            (w, h) = (boxes[i][2], boxes[i][3])
            # Draw the bounding box rectangle and label each one then add to the frame
            color = [int(c) for c in COLORS[classIDs[i]]]
            cv2.rectangle(frame, (x, y), (x + w, y + h), color, 2)
            text = "{}: {:.4f}".format(LABELS[classIDs[i]], confidences[i])
            cv2.putText(frame, text, (x, y - 5), cv2.FONT_HERSHEY_SIMPLEX, H * FONT_SCALE, color, 2)
            
    # Initialize writer for the output video if it is not already done
    if writer is None:
        # Define the codec and create video writer
        fourcc = cv2.VideoWriter_fourcc(*"MJPG")
        writer = cv2.VideoWriter(OUTPUT_VIDEO, fourcc, 30, (frame.shape[1], frame.shape[0]), True)
        # Estimation of process time at the beginning
        if total > 0:
            elap = (end - start)
            print("[INFO] single frame took {:.4f} seconds".format(elap))
            print("[INFO] estimated total time to finish: {:.4f}".format(elap * total))
    
    # Write the output frame to the output video
    writer.write(frame)
    
    # Show 1 processed frame in the middle of the output video
    if (image_index == int(total/2)):
        fig_width, fig_height = plt.gcf().get_size_inches()
        plt.figure(figsize=(fig_width*3,fig_height*3))
        plt.title('Processed frame', fontsize=16)
        plt.axis('off')
        plt.imshow(frame)
        plt.show()

[INFO] estimated total time to finish: 406.5612
